The White House hosted a virtual Eviction Prevention Summit, the first of its kind, aimed at preventing evictions and stabilizing families. The summit consisted of a public plenary session on eviction prevention best practices and breakout sessions for various stakeholders to develop eviction prevention action plans for their local areas. The Administration announced actions to encourage the disbursement of over $46 billion in emergency rental assistance to assist households in need. Several speakers highlighted the importance of emergency rental assistance and eviction diversion programs in preventing a wave of new evictions. The summit concluded with attendees splitting into groups to develop eviction prevention action plans for their cities.